## Breeding

Platy breeding follows the livebearer model — internal fertilisation, gestation, and live birth of free-swimming fry.

**Gestation:** 24–35 days. Females give birth approximately every 4–6 weeks under good conditions.

**Fry size at birth:** Platy fry are among the larger livebearer fry — approximately 6–8mm — making them easier to raise than some other species.

**Fry count per birth:** 20–80 depending on female age, size, and condition.

**Fry foods from birth:**
- **Baby Brine Shrimp nauplii** — **[From Blackwater Aquatics](https://blackwateraquatics.ca/collections/live-foods)**
- Finely crushed flake food
- **Microworms** — **[From Blackwater Aquatics](https://blackwateraquatics.ca/collections/live-foods)**

**Colour expression in fry:** Colour begins developing at 3–4 weeks. By 6–8 weeks most colour patterns are visible. Sex determination at 4–6 weeks (males develop gonopodium, the modified anal fin used for internal fertilisation).

**Sperm storage:** Like all poecilid livebearers, females store sperm and can produce multiple broods from a single mating. A female kept without males for 6 months can still be "pregnant."

### Genetic Interest

The Xiphophorus genus has been the subject of extensive genetics research — specifically the spontaneous melanoma (black pigmentation tumour) that develops in certain hybrids between X. maculatus and Swordtails. The *Xiphophorus* melanoma research program contributed foundational knowledge to human melanoma biology. Your Platies are, historically, contributors to cancer research.

